The '''mountain blackeye'''{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}} ('''''Zosterops emiliae'''''), sometimes referred to as the '''olive blackeye''' or simply '''black-eye''', is a [[species]] of [[passerine]] bird in the family [[Zosteropidae]]. It is endemic to the highest mountains on the island of [[Borneo]]. It is known from both [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|Malaysian states]] on the island, and four of the five Indonesian provinces, but has never been recorded in [[Brunei]]. Typically found at elevations above {{convert|1800|m|abbr=on}}, the mountain blackeye sometimes moves to lower altitudes during periods of drought. There are four subspecies, which show [[cline (biology)|clinal variation]]s in size and coloring. Birds in the north are largest, darkest, and proportionately longer-tailed, while those further south are smaller, paler, and proportionately shorter-tailed. Adults are dark olive-green with a sharply-pointed, bright yellow-orange [[beak|bill]] and a small dark mask connecting black {{birdgloss|lores}} with a black {{birdgloss|eye-ring}}. The subspecies show varying amounts of yellow in their [[plumage]], particularly on the face and underparts. Young birds resemble their parents, but have less brightly colored bills.

It feeds on insects, nectar, pollen, and small fruits, and is a major pollinator of several species of ''[[Rhododendron]]''. It is also a minor partner in a [[symbiotic relationship]] with the pitcher-plant ''[[Nepenthes lowii]]''. Little is known about its breeding ecology. Its [[bird nest|nest]] is a shallow cup made of rootlets and lined with bits of moss. The female lays a single egg, and the nestling takes 14–15 days to {{birdgloss|fledge}} after hatching. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] lists it as a species of [[least concern]]. Although its population has not been quantified, it is very common across much of its range.

==Taxonomy and systematics==
[[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]] first described the mountain blackeye in 1888, using a specimen collected on [[Mount Kinabalu]] in northern Borneo. He named it ''Chlorocharis emiliae'',<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/55018#page/420/ Ibis V6(series 5), pp.392-393 Further Descriptions of new species of Birds collected by  Mr.John Whitehead on the Mountain of Kina Balu, North Borneo]</ref> putting it into a [[monotypic]] [[genus]] that he created for the species.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=483}} It remained in that genus for more than a century, with its affinities to other members of [[white-eye|Zosteropidae]] (white-eye) family unclear.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=407}} However, [[molecular phylogenetic]] studies done early in the 21st century showed that it actually nested comfortably within the genus ''[[Zosterops]]'', leading ''Chlorocharis'' to be [[wikt:subsumed|subsumed]] into that larger genus.{{sfn|Moyle|Filardi|Smith|Diamond|2009|p=1864}}{{sfn|Lim|Sadanandan|Dingle|Leung|2018|p=13}} Phylogenetic studies have shown that it is more closely related to species on other [[Sundaland]] islands than it is to species in Borneo's lowlands.{{sfn|Gawin|Rahman|Ramji|Smith|2014|p=87}}

There are four recognized subspecies.{{sfn|Gill|Donsker|Rasmussen|2021}}{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=407}} These show a [[clinal variation]]. Those in the north are the largest, darkest, and relatively longest-tailed, while those in the south are the smallest, palest, and relatively shortest-tailed.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=407}} [[Mitochondrial DNA]] studies have shown that the species divides neatly into two clades, one in [[Sabah]] and the other in [[Sarawak]].{{sfn|Gawin|Rahman|Ramji|Smith|2014|p=93}} Researchers theorize that the subspecies that make up the two clades were separated by [[ice age|glacial event]]s, diverging as long ago as the mid-[[Pleistocene]].{{sfn|Gawin|Rahman|Ramji|Smith|2014|p=93}}

* ''Z. e. emiliae'', described by Sharpe in 1888, is found on [[Mount Kinabalu]] and [[Mount Tambuyukon]], which are both located in the Malaysian state of Sabah.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=483}}
* ''Z. e. trinitae'', first described by [[Tom Harrisson]] in 1957, is found on [[Mount Trus Madi]] in Sabah.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=483}}
* ''Z. e. fusciceps'', first described in 1954 by [[Gerlof Mees]], is found in the southern part of the [[Crocker Range]], in the [[Maga Mountains]].{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=483}}
* ''Z. e. moultani'', first described in 1927 by [[Frederick Nutter Chasen]] and [[Cecil Boden Kloss]], is found in western Sarawak and [[West Kalimantan]].{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}}

The genus name ''Zosterops'' is a combination of the [[Ancient Greek]] words ''zoster'', meaning "girdle" or "belt" and ''ops'' meaning "eye".{{sfn|Jobling|2010|p=414}} The [[species name]] ''emiliae'' has been said to commemorate Emilie Hose, wife of [[Charles Hose]], an English administrator, naturalist and collector,{{sfn|Jobling|2010|p=146}} but this was not explained by Bowdler Sharpe and seems mistaken. Other common names include '''olive blackeye''' or simply '''black-eye'''.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=483}}

==Description==
[[file:Chlorocharis emiliae Keulemans.jpg|thumb|left|Illustrated by [[John Gerrard Keulemans|Keulemans]] (1888)]]
The mountain blackeye is a small [[passerine]], ranging in length from {{convert|11|to|14|cm|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}}{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}}{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=272}} Compared to most other white-eyes, it is larger and longer-tailed.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=407}} The only known measured individual (sex unknown) weighed {{convert|13.9|g|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}} Male and female are similarly plumaged.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}} The adult of the nominate race, ''emiliae'', is dark olive-green on the head and upperparts with a blackish tinge to the green, particularly on the {{birdgloss|crown}}. Its underparts are somewhat paler, with a yellowish tint, particularly towards the center of the belly. It has a black {{birdgloss|eye-ring}} and black [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]], which connect to form a small dark mask, edged by a yellow border.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}} It has a bright yellow-green {{birdgloss|supraloral}} and throat.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}} Its [[iris (anatomy)|iris]] is brown, and its long, slender, pointed, [[wiktionary|decurved]] [[beak|bill]] is brown on the {{birdgloss|upper mandible}} and bright yellow-orange on the lower. Its legs and feet are dark yellowish-brown to black, with yellow [[sole (foot)|sole]]s. The immature bird is like the adult, though with a duller-colored bill; this is typically dull orange to blackish.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}}

The subspecies ''trinitae'' is similar to ''emiliae'', but brighter and more yellowish overall. Its belly is almost completely yellow, and it shows more yellow on the face. The subspecies ''fusciceps'' is smaller and relatively shorter-tailed than ''emiliae'', with a [[Sepia (color)|sepia]] tint to its crown and forehead.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}} Its underparts are yellow.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}} The subspecies ''moultoni'' is similar to ''fusciceps''. It is the palest of the subspecies, showing more yellow in its plumage;{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}} its underparts are dark green.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}}

