===Vocalizations===
The mountain blackeye has a melodious song, variously transcribed as "''wit-weet-weet-weet-weetee-weetee-tee''" or "''werwit-kukewtoweeo''".{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}}{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=256}} It also sings a shorter ''titiweeio''".{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=256}} One of its calls is a sharp "''pweet''".{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}} Its wings make a distinctive noise when it flies: a whirring ''trrt trrt'',{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=272}} while its flight call is transcribed as "''gujuguju''" (with a short "u" sound). It has a trio of perching calls: "''wi-u''", "''siwi-u''", and "''ie-wio''".{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=257}}

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Mount Kinabalu Foggy Scenery.jpg|thumb|The mountain blackeye is the most common bird in summit scrub, such as this on [[Mount Kinabalu]].|alt=A steep slope covered with short, dense, brushy scrub under heavy cloud and fog]]
The mountain blackeye is [[endemic]] to the high mountains of Borneo, where it is the most common bird on the summit slopes of the island's highest mountains: Kinabalu, Tambuyukon and Trus Madi.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=272}} It is also found on several isolated lower mountains.{{sfn|Gawin|Rahman|Ramji|Smith|2014|p=88}} It occurs in both Malaysian states (Sabah and Sarawak) and four of the five Indonesian provinces ([[North Kalimantan]], [[East Kalimantan]], [[Central Kalimantan]], and West Kalimantan) on the island, but has never been recorded in [[Brunei]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}}{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=272}} Its habitats include primary [[Borneo montane rain forests|upper montane forest]], summit scrub, and gully vegetation.{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=256}} While it generally occurs at elevations above {{convert|1800|m|abbr=on}}, it may move to lower elevations during periods of drought.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=272}}

==Ecology==
Much of the life history and ecology of the mountain blackeye is not well-known.{{sfn|Gawin|Rahman|Ramji|Smith|2014|p=88}} The species is {{birdgloss|resident}}, with no migratory movements.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}} Its generation length is estimated at 4.4 years.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}}

===Feeding===
[[File:Mountain Blackeye.jpg|thumb|The mountain blackeye's diet includes nectar, pollen, insects, and small berries.|alt=Olive-green bird with an orange bill and black eye-ring eating a small green berry.]]
The mountain blackeye feeds on nectar, pollen, insects (particularly [[caterpillar]]s, [[grasshopper]]s and [[beetle]]s), and small berries, including [[raspberry|raspberries]].{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=272}}{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=257}} It has a modified tongue—tubular with a brush-like tip—which allows it to easily sip nectar.{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=256}} It feeds at all heights, from the ground to the canopy, often foraging in small groups.{{sfn|Myers|2016|p=268}} It visits the flowers of ''[[Eugenia]]'', ''[[Schima]]'', ''[[Elaeocarpus]]'' and several ''[[Rhododendron]]'' species.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}}{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=549}} Studies indicate that it may be an important pollinator of ''[[Rhododendron buxifolium]]''; it also regularly visits ''[[Rhododendron ericoides]]'' and ''[[Rhododendron acuminatum]]''.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}}{{sfn|Kudo|Suzuki|2004|pp=564–565}} It is an occasional partner in a [[symbiotic relationship]] with ''[[Nepenthes lowii]]'', a pitcher-plant which is also endemic to Borneo. The plant produces waxy secretions on the lid of its pitcher.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=371}} Although [[treeshrew]]s are the primary consumers of these secretions, mountain blackeyes also partake, sometimes [[defecation|defecating]] into the pitchers as they do so.{{sfn|Chin|Moran|Clarke|2010|p=465}} Treeshrew and bird [[feces]] provide nutrients for the plant; studies have shown that some plants get 57–100% of their nitrogen from animal feces.{{sfn|Chin|Moran|Clarke|2010|p=464}} Because the waxy secretions are produced year-round, they can be an important food source for mountain blackeyes when other plants are not in flower, or when insects are hard to find.{{sfn|Phillipps|Phillipps|2014|p=371}}

===Breeding===
The breeding ecology of the mountain blackeye is only poorly known.{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=256}} It breeds in February, March, June, and September.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}} The [[bird nest|nest]] is a shallow cup made of rootlets and dried grass, and lined with the [[sporophyte]] stalks or [[setae]] of [[moss]]es. It measures roughly {{convert|7.5|cm|abbr=on}} across and is typically built in the fork of a branch of a ''[[Leptospermum]]'' tree within {{convert|1|to|8|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} of the ground.{{sfn|van Balen|2008|p=484}}{{sfn|Sheldon|Moyle|Kennard|2001|p=256}} The female lays a single egg, and the hatched {{birdgloss|nestling}} takes 14–15 days to {{birdgloss|fledge}}.{{sfn|Mitchell|Boersma|Anthony|Kitayama|2020}} Because of the low temperatures and high moisture levels at the elevations where mountain blackeyes breed, the birds spend considerable time incubating their chick early in its development, when it cannot [[thermoregulation|regulate its own body temperature]]. This means that they spend less time foraging for food for the chick, which delays its development. When nests were experimentally heated and covered against the rain, parents spent less time at the nest, chicks gained weight faster, grew wing feathers quicker, and fledged earlier.{{sfn|Mitchell|Boersma|Anthony|Kitayama|2020}}

==Status==
The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] rates the mountain blackeye as a species of [[least concern]]. Although it is range-restricted, it is very common across much of its range, though western populations are much more localized. Its overall population size has not been quantified, but it is thought to be declining, primarily due to [[habitat destruction]] and fragmentation.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2016}} Much of its range is protected by parks or forest reserves, including [[Kinabalu Park]] (which protects Mounts Kinabalu and Tambuyukon),{{sfn|Choi|Tsuey|Biun|Adam|2011|p=3318}} and [[Crocker Range National Park|Crocker Range Park]] (which protects much of the area around Mount Kinabalu).{{sfn|Sabah Parks|2021}} However, protection does not necessarily forestall habitat destruction, as for example, permission has been granted for extensive logging in the forest reserve on Mount Trus Madi.{{sfn|Borneo Today|2017}}

